  "prompt": "What are the best dialogues from the movie Masaan?",
  "response": "\"Masaan\" is a poignant and critically acclaimed Indian film that features several memorable dialogues. Here are some of the best dialogues from the movie:\n\n1. **\"Kuch log unn raaston se jaate hain jo unke liye bane hi nahi the.\"**\n   - \"Some people take paths that were never meant for them.\"\n   - This line reflects the existential struggle of the characters as they navigate life's unexpected challenges.\n\n2. **\"Main apni kismat se nahi, apne faislein se apni zindagi banata hoon.\"**\n   - \"I don't build my life with my fate, but with my decisions.\"\n   - This dialogue encapsulates the theme of agency and personal responsibility, as spoken by the character Deepak.\n\n3. **\"Zindagi jeene ke do hi tarike hote hain, ek jo ho raha hai use hone do, doosra khud ko badal do.\"**\n   - \"There are only two ways to live life, one is to let things happen as they are, the other is to change yourself.\"\n   - This powerful line, spoken by Pathak, highlights the philosophical undertones of the film about living life on one's own terms.\n\n4. **\"Sab kuch seedha nahi hota, sab kuch seedha nahi hota.\"**\n   - \"Everything is not straightforward, everything is not straightforward.\"\n   - This dialogue, repeated by Devi, underscores the complexity and unpredictability of life, reflecting her internal turmoil.\n\n5. **\"Maut ek din sabko aani hai, lekin zindagi roz aati hai, roz.\"**\n   - \"Death comes to everyone one day, but life comes every day, every day.\"\n   - This line by Shukla Ji emphasizes the importance of living in the present and making the most of each day.\n\nThese dialogues not only capture the essence of the film but also resonate deeply with the audience, reflecting universal themes of life, death, and personal growth.",
